replies.bodyText:
You could probably do a "top N" type of sort where you only keep the lowest loaded node, but it would require a bit of a refactor of getLowerLoadNodes, probably changing it to getLowestLodeNode. That would avoid a full sort and would not be much more expensive that the current code, eg:
DatanodeDetails lowest = null;
int lowestPipelineCount;
for (DatanodeDetails dn : nodes) {
  int nodePipelines = node.getPipelineCount();
  if (nodePipelines > limit) {
    continue;
  }
  if ((lowest == null) || lowestPipelineCount > nodePipelines {
    lowest = node;
    lowestPipelineCount = nodePipelines;
  }
}
return lowest;

